<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-201-310  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 201 310.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  March 5 1990 v16 n5 p13(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Mobile satellite systems get ready to roll. (ultra-compact,inexpensive satellite receivers expand into a variety ofapplications)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Davis, Dwight B.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The satellite data transmission market is growing as thetechnology is enhanced, creating a new market for mobile satellitepositioning and messaging systems.andP;  One industry analyst predictsthat the current installed base of approximately 20,000 terminalswill experience a compounded annual growth rate of 150 percentthrough 1994.andP;  Geostar Corp was the first US company to attractmobile satellite users in 1987 with its mobile positioning andmessaging service.andP;  Qualcomm Inc, in 1988, offered the firsttwo-way messaging system.andP;  American Mobile Satellite Corp (AMSC),a consortium of eight major telecommunications firms, will beginproviding services in 1990.andP;  Qualcomm has the largest mobilesatellite contract, to provide a tracking system for a fleet ofabout 5,000 trucks, and the largest market share.andP;  Geostar andAMSC, along with new entrants to the market, are planning to offerincreased satellite services in the early 1990s.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Geostar Corp. (marketing)Qualcomm Inc. (marketing)American Mobile Satellite Corp. (marketing).andO;Topic:     Satellite CommunicationsMarketing StrategyTracking SystemsCompetitionTrends.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Worldwide revenue of satellite systems: boom in sales ispredicted. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>